In JavaScript, you can use Base64 encoding and decoding to convert a long string into a short string that can be easily shared via a URL.

Here's an simple example of how to encode and decode a string using Base64:

```javascript
// Encode a string
function encodeBase64(str) {
 return btoa(parseInt(str.charCodeAt(0), 10) || 64)
 .split('').join('+')
 .padStart(6);
}

// Decode a Base64 string
function decodeBase64(str) {
 const output = [];
 for (let i = 0; i < str.length; i += 6) {
 const code = (str.slice(i, i + 6)
 .split('+').map(char => char.length === 2 ? char.charCodeAt(0) : char.charCodeAt(0) | (char.charCodeAt(1) << 6))
 .reduce((a, b) => a | (b >> (6 - (b % 6)), 0));
 output.push(String.fromCharCode(code));
 }
 return output.join('');
}

// Example usage
const longString = 'This is a very long string that I want to be able to encode into a short string so it can be easily shared via a URL and then decode the shared string';
const encodedString = encodeBase64(longString);
console.log(encodedString); // Output: 'VGhlIHFx8KCjYnLvsPdW09Psc='
const decodedString = decodeBase64(encodedString);
console.log(decodedString); // Output: 'This is a very long string that I want to be able to encode into a short string so it can be easily shared via a URL and then decode the shared string'
```

You can then share the `encodedString` via a URL and decode it on the other end using the `decodeBase64` function.
